  "text": "The objective of this study is to provide preliminary evidence for the OPJE in a choice context. Consumers often face situations in which they may choose between a hedonic and a utilitarian option. If the two options are presented separately, people are likely to evaluate the hedonic option more favorably than the utilitarian option. However, this effect is greatly attenuated when both options are presented together because it is harder to justify purchasing the hedonic product in that situation [CITATION_1] . In Study 1, we test the OPJE in a choice context by investigating how odd-ending prices affect preferences for hedonic versus utilitarian options.",
  "correct_citation": {
